   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "1507be49-16aa-4b4b-9eed-f3c9a7891ef5",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Ligand-based Pharmacophores\n",
    "\n",
    "Pharmacophores can be obtanied from a set of ligands that are known to have activity against the receptor of interest. This is called ligand-based pharmacophore modelling and it is usually carried out by extracting common chemical features from 3D structures of a set of known ligands representative of essential interactions between the ligands and a specific macromolecular target. \n",
    "\n",
    "A variety of methods exists to extract a common pharmacophore from a set of ligands. Different algorithms such as the genetic algorithm, clique detection, gibbs sampling, etc. have been used succesfully to derive ligand-based pharmacophores. Currently OpenPharmacophore only supports a algorithm based on density based cluestering. Future versions of the library will implement other algorithms.\n",
    "\n",
    "In this tutorial we will explore how to construct ligand based pharmacophores with OpenPharmacophore. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "id": "cdb5ebbb-97df-4652-be86-17dd707886d4",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {

      },
      "text/plain": []
     },

     "output_type": "display_data"

    "from openpharmacophore.utils.load_custom_feats import load_smarts_fdef\n",

    "from rdkit import RDLogger \n",
    "RDLogger.DisableLog('rdApp.*')\n",
    "\n",
    "from IPython.display import Image"

   "source": [
    "## Pharmacophore for Non-Peptide Angiotensin II Receptor antagonists\n",
    "\n",
    "We will derive a pharmacophore model from a set of 5 ligands of the non-peptide angiotensin receptor. \n",
    "\n",
    "A ligand-based pharmacophore can be created using the LiganBasedPharmacophore class. A pharmacophore then can be created from a list of rdkit molecules or by passing a molecule file such as a smi, mol2 or sdf file. \n",
    "\n",
    "The LiganBasedPharmacophore class is derived from the Pharmacophore class, so it functions in a similar way.\n",
    "\n",
    "We will obtain the pharmacophore model from a list of rdkit molecules."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "id": "5b67bc23-8bf9-45a7-a1ea-3e37e84b3e3d",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "5 molecules\n"
     ]
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<PIL.PngImagePlugin.PngImageFile image mode=RGB size=1000x200 at 0x7F9A80DCBB90>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 2,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Load the molecules and visualize them\n",
    "molecules = Chem.SmilesMolSupplier('../../../openpharmacophore/data/ligands/clique_detection.smi',delimiter='\\t',titleLine=False)\n",
    "print(f\"{len(molecules)} molecules\")\n",
    "img = Draw.MolsToGridImage(molecules, molsPerRow=5, returnPNG=False)\n",
    "img"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a2edcbcb-4329-49be-ba53-9240de4ca271",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "To create the pharmacophore the class method from_ligand_list can be used. Otherwise, the from_file method can be used. Besides the ligands, this method also expects a \"method\" argument, a \"feat_list\" and a \"feat_def\" argument.\n",
    "\n",
    "The \"method\" argument is the algorithm that will be used to obtain the common pharmacophore. Currently, only the density based clustering algorithm or dbscan is implemented.\n",
    "\n",
    "\"feat_list\" is a an optional list with the pharmacophoric features that will be taken into account. For example, if we would like to obtain a pharmacophore with only hydrogen bond donors an aromatic rings we wil pass the list [\"hb donor\", \"aromatic ring\"]\n",
    "\n",
    "The \"feat_def\" argument stands for feature definition. A feature definition is a set of smarts strings that are used to define chemical features within a ligand. Openpharmacophore uses the default definition implemented in rdkit; however, a custom definion can be passed as we will do in this example."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "id": "012332f3-4ff5-4671-9180-d71226787fef",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "# lines started from # are comments\n",
      "#\n",
      "# each line is SMARTS and feature label\n",
      "#\n",
      "# Aromatic\n",
      "a1aaaaa1 Aromatic\n",
      "a1aaaa1 Aromatic\n",
      "\n",
      "# HBD\n",
      "[#7!H0&!$(N-[SX4](=O)(=O)[CX4](F)(F)F)] Donor\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Let's load a custom feature definition\n",
    "# First take a look at the file\n",
    "! head ../../../openpharmacophore/data/smarts_features.txt -n 10"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "c96c53e6-f7e2-496c-9127-185bf17960f1",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "A custom feature defintion can be loaded froma file similar to the one above. This is a file with the smarts strings followed by the name of the chemical feature. We can use the function load_smarts_fdef to obtain a dictionary of smarts and feature names."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "id": "b75806fe-e8dc-4e63-a966-95eaa783840a",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "{'a1aaaaa1': 'Aromatic',\n",
       " 'a1aaaa1': 'Aromatic',\n",
       " '[#7!H0&!$(N-[SX4](=O)(=O)[CX4](F)(F)F)]': 'Donor',\n",
       " '[#8!H0&!$([OH][C,S,P]=O)]': 'Donor',\n",
       " '[#16!H0]': 'Donor',\n",
       " '[#7&!$([nX3])&!$([NX3]-*=[!#6])&!$([NX3]-[a])&!$([NX4])&!$(N=C([C,N])N)]': 'Acceptor',\n",
       " '[$([O])&!$([OX2](C)C=O)&!$(*(~a)~a)]': 'Acceptor',\n",
       " '[$([NX3]([CX4])([CX4,#1])[CX4,#1])&!$([NX3]-*=[!#6])]': 'PosIonizable',\n",
       " '[$([CX3](=N)(-N)[!N])](=N)-N': 'PosIonizable',\n",
       " 'N=[CX3](N)-N': 'PosIonizable',\n",
       " '[$([+,+2,+3])&!$(*[-,-2,-3])]': 'PosIonizable',\n",
       " 'c1nn[nH1]n1': 'NegIonizable',\n",
       " '[$([SX4,PX4](=O)(=O)[O-,OH])](=O)(=O)[O-,OH]': 'NegIonizable',\n",
       " '[$([CX3,SX3,PX3](=O)[O-,OH])](=O)[O-,OH]': 'NegIonizable',\n",
       " '[$([-,-2,-3])&!$(*[+,+2,+3])]': 'NegIonizable',\n",
       " '[$([CH3X4,CH2X3,CH1X2,F,Cl,Br,I])&!$(**[CH3X4,CH2X3,CH1X2,F,Cl,Br,I])]': 'Hydrophobe',\n",
       " '[$(*([CH3X4,CH2X3,CH1X2,F,Cl,Br,I])[CH3X4,CH2X3,CH1X2,F,Cl,Br,I])&!$(*([CH3X4,CH2X3,CH1X2,F,Cl,Br,I])([CH3X4,CH2X3,CH1X2,F,Cl,Br,I])[CH3X4,CH2X3,CH1X2,F,Cl,Br,I])]([CH3X4,CH2X3,CH1X2,F,Cl,Br,I])[CH3X4,CH2X3,CH1X2,F,Cl,Br,I]': 'Hydrophobe',\n",
       " '*([CH3X4,CH2X3,CH1X2,F,Cl,Br,I])([CH3X4,CH2X3,CH1X2,F,Cl,Br,I])[CH3X4,CH2X3,CH1X2,F,Cl,Br,I]': 'Hydrophobe',\n",
       " '[C&r3]1~[C&r3]~[C&r3]1': 'Hydrophobe',\n",
       " '[C&r4]1~[C&r4]~[C&r4]~[C&r4]1': 'Hydrophobe',\n",
       " '[C&r5]1~[C&r5]~[C&r5]~[C&r5]~[C&r5]1': 'Hydrophobe',\n",
       " '[C&r6]1~[C&r6]~[C&r6]~[C&r6]~[C&r6]~[C&r6]1': 'Hydrophobe',\n",
       " '[C&r7]1~[C&r7]~[C&r7]~[C&r7]~[C&r7]~[C&r7]~[C&r7]1': 'Hydrophobe',\n",
       " '[C&r8]1~[C&r8]~[C&r8]~[C&r8]~[C&r8]~[C&r8]~[C&r8]~[C&r8]1': 'Hydrophobe',\n",
       " '[CH2X4,CH1X3,CH0X2]~[CH3X4,CH2X3,CH1X2,F,Cl,Br,I]': 'Hydrophobe',\n",
       " '[$([CH2X4,CH1X3,CH0X2]~[$([!#1]);!$([CH2X4,CH1X3,CH0X2])])]~[CH2X4,CH1X3,CH0X2]~[CH2X4,CH1X3,CH0X2]': 'Hydrophobe',\n",
       " '[$([CH2X4,CH1X3,CH0X2]~[CH2X4,CH1X3,CH0X2]~[$([CH2X4,CH1X3,CH0X2]~[$([!#1]);!$([CH2X4,CH1X3,CH0X2])])])]~[CH2X4,CH1X3,CH0X2]~[CH2X4,CH1X3,CH0X2]~[CH2X4,CH1X3,CH0X2]': 'Hydrophobe',\n",
       " '[$([S]~[#6])&!$(S~[!#6])]': 'Hydrophobe'}"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 4,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "feat_def = load_smarts_fdef(\"../../../openpharmacophore/data/smarts_features.txt\")\n",
    "feat_def"
   ]
  },

    "Now we are ready to create the pharmacophore"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",

    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Create the pharmacophore\n",
    "molecules = list(molecules)\n",
    "pharmacophore = LigandBasedPharmacophore().from_ligand_list(ligands=molecules, \n",
    "                                                            method=\"dbscan\", \n",
    "                                                            feat_list=None, \n",
    "                                                            feat_def=feat_def)\n",
    "print(pharmacophore)"
   ]
  },
